For more than ten days, Giselle had used her 'illness' as an excuse to justify her disappearance. Although many believed it, some still frowned.

 "My, how delicate It would be a problem if she stains our pamphlets with nosebleeds. Wouldn't it be better to rest at home?"  "Don't worry. Duke Eccleston would compensate for any damage."

The student visibly paled, abandoned his attitude, and retreated. Rita let out a satisfied chuckle.

That was her little pleasure: seeing how those brats who scorned 'the Roselle who thinks she's a princess' bowed down at the mention of the Duke. Whenever she could, she played that card.

That day, although no one openly provoked Giselle during the club meeting, the students who flattered her, believing she was an 'Eccleston noble,' surrounded her. Rita, as always, took advantage:

 "Miss, we must leave. His Excellency the Duke is waiting for you."

But when they were alone, Rita never mentioned the 'Duke.' Before, she used to speak of him with admiration, but after that day, she stopped. Perhaps out of fear of making Giselle uncomfortable.

However, Giselle didn't care. Maybe the adversities had hardened her. Or perhaps, after Edwin had seen her at her worst, shame no longer affected her. Or she had simply learned to value that they were both still alive.

It's him!

In the end, all that mattered was that, upon seeing him after such a long time, she only felt joy.

The car stopped in front of the residence. As she stepped out, the main door opened. She expected to see the butler, but it was he who came out to greet her.

 "Welcome."

Have his wounds already healed? What a relief. Only after confirming he wore no bandages on his hands did Giselle look up to study his face.

And then, her steps toward him stopped dead.

Her eyes, full of disbelief, swept over Rita, Loise, and the rest of the staff around them. Everyone was smiling courteously, as if nothing was abnormal.

