The dog, panting and looking at Giselle, lowered his head and scratched an ear with his hind paw.

 "Well, he has a skin problem, but he's clean. The vet gave us an ointment. Tell a maid to apply it every day. The Duke will cover the expenses."  "......."  "I gave him a name: Eddie."

He gave his childhood nickname to a dog?

For the first time, Giselle's impassive expression broke. The demon noticed and, smiling with satisfaction, extended the leash toward her.

 "This time, raise him until the end."

This is how you want me to redeem myself? You, of all people, dare to ask me that?

She burned with desire to confront him, but neither the time nor the place was right.

 "Understood. Now leave."  "You have to raise him."  "I said yes!"

Only when Rita took the leash instead did the struggle end.

 "It was a pleasure seeing you, sweetheart. Enjoy dinner and next time, we'll have dinner together."  "Yes, yes."

It was obvious Giselle was replying out of obligation, but apparently, that was enough for the cunning demon.

 "Dawson, take the dog."

And just like that, as if nothing happened, the Duke (Edwin) regained his body and left.

 "That the demon listened to Miss Bishop"

For Loise, it was a shock but also a hopeful sign.

Edwin had tried to cancel the dinner, but Giselle's stubbornness prevailed, and they eventually shared the meal as planned.

Under the watchful eyes of Dawson and Loise, sitting at opposite ends of the dining room, the conversation flowed from trivialities to more personal topics. Edwin, whose life no longer had room for the 'everyday,' could only talk about her.

 "Anything interesting at school today?"  "No, the usual. Classes, homework, and helping with the club's event preparations."

Upon mentioning that the Patriotic Student Society was busy organizing an event for Veteran's Day at the National Memorial, Giselle remembered a favor the club president had asked her last week.

 "The club will auction off personal items from celebrities to raise funds for military hospitals"

It was only possible because all the club members had influential connections.

 "Could you donate something, Lord? It doesn't have to be valuable even something small you've personally used. People would bid like crazy for it."  "Something small? Would a handkerchief that has touched my lips suffice?"  "No!"

It was the first time in a long time that Edwin had joked with that playful malice. Giselle loved that glimpse of his old self, even though the joke itself deeply displeased her.

Imagining women waving their bids for a piece of cloth that grazed his lips Just thinking about it gave her a shiver of disgust.
Chapter 130.
In her imagination, Giselle couldn't bear the thought of the mark of Edwin's lips ending up in the hands of another woman, so, betting all her fortune, from national bonds to the house on Magnolia Terrace, she bought that worthless rag back for just a few coins.

How pathetic. It was only a fantasy, and yet she felt miserable. But fantasies, in the end, are the most honest reflection of oneself.

Edwin, thinking Giselle's anger was just a fit of pique, winked at her with an amused smile, but then began to take her seriously.

 "So what would be suitable?"  "Well something one would recommend but never read again or a tie that's no longer worn because it went out of style"  "Shall we look for something after dinner?"  "Of course."

Of course. That way, she would at least have the perfect excuse: being able to personally choose something that wouldn't hurt if it ended up in another woman's hands, and, furthermore, avoiding having to leave immediately after the meal.

 "Do you enjoy being in the Patriotic Student Society?"  "Yes, I do."

But Edwin's instinct told him Giselle was lying.

 "And is there no one bothering you?"

He knew perfectly well Giselle would answer no, but he asked anyway.

 "Yes, there is."

And he received an answer he didn't expect.

