He was ready to not forgive whoever it was, but Giselle began to enumerate, one after another, the professors from her classes. Edwin's rigid face relaxed, revealing a smile. That Giselle had returned to her daily routine was already a relief, but that she also had the lightness to joke as if nothing had happened, filled him with gratitude.

 "How dare they overburden my little one with assignments? This cannot stand. Royce, call the dean right now."

Edwin also pretended that nothing was wrong, but he couldn't fool himself: he knew Giselle was not as well as she appeared.

How is one supposed to forget what they lived through while imprisoned? One only survives, enduring it.

Like the guilt she carried for the dogs she had to kill in order to stay alive.

 "If I hadn't eaten them myself, someone else would have stolen them or I would have starved to death. That would have been sadder, don't you think?"

When asked how she had obtained food in those days, the 'Natalia' of then confessed, unintentionally, that she even ate the dogs she had raised. She immediately became nervous and tried to justify it to Edwin. But he wasn't disappointed; instead, he marveled at the tenacity and courage of a child barely ten years old.

 "Of course. You did well. Natalia is brave."

Since that day, they never spoke of the subject again, and Edwin had completely forgotten about it. He thought Giselle had too but he was wrong.

So that's why she turned so pale when she saw that dog on the street last time.

When she said she wasn't afraid of dogs, she was probably sincere. What she was afraid of wasn't the dogs, but the memories.

No dogs were raised at Templeton Mansion, so Giselle practically had no chance of running into one. When she was little, Edwin asked her if she wanted a puppy. She said no, and he, naively, thought it simply wasn't to her liking. How insensitive he had been.

'Giselle, I truly believe that surviving the way you did was brave and intelligent. What you did is not a sin. On the contrary, it is proof that you are destined for great things. Don't be ashamed, be proud.'

That was, and still was, Edwin's sincere conviction. But for a child who suffered so much she contemplated death, even the best words were nothing more than fuel for a memory turned nightmare. That's why, since then, he had kept his opinions to himself and yet

'That bastard, how dare he.'

As soon as Edwin made plans to see Giselle, that fellow ignored his warning and stole his body.

 "Giselle says she wants to have a dog. I was just thinking we could use a guard dog."

Speaking as if he were Edwin, he ordered Royce to bring a dog. No less than a mongrel from a shelter. As if he wanted to dig into Giselle's wounds

'That's not true.'

The madman inside his head immediately denied it, with a tone of false indignation. But how could he believe him, when his actions said otherwise?

After calling Giselle the Duke's pet and a leech, treating her as less than human, what else could that dog seem like but a mockery?

'I only behaved as you taught me.'

And as if nothing, he blamed Edwin, saying he had only imitated him by not treating her as a person.

'You want to be treated like a human being? Then start by behaving like one. Who acts like that with a woman they like?'

This time, he received no response. The other remained silent, without arguments.

'You say you are following my example? Don't make me laugh.'

If he really acted like Edwin, then how would he explain daring to pry at Giselle's wounds, the ones he never touched?

'Is this perhaps your way of apologizing? And what good is regret if you do everything wrong?'

If he was capable of imitating Edwin with such precision, why did he behave so differently with women? It was enough to remember how Edwin treated women to know what to do and what to avoid. Even if he didn't have many references, just by following the courtesy and common sense that defined Edwin, he could have been a perfect gentleman for Giselle.

But someone who knew how to follow Edwin's respect and judgment would never have violated Giselle as an act of revenge.

'To do something like that and then say you like her You lack not only conscience, but also intelligence. You? You dare to set your sights on Giselle?'

She, the most precious creature in this world, was too much for anyone. Even the most upright and brilliant men couldn't measure up to her. And yet, that nameless lout, little more than a thug, dared to court her saying he liked her. If he could have, he would have chased him away like the regular client of a brothel, just as he did with Giselle's past dates.

While holding a light conversation with Giselle, his thoughts, sharp as blades, came to an abrupt halt. Something in front of his eyes had suddenly changed. They were still in the dining room, sitting opposite each other, but Royce and Dawson, who were previously waiting discreetly by the wall, had now approached the table. Everyone, except Giselle, showed tension on their faces.

