It was the second time that fellow had appeared. Giselle, fearing that her uncle might suggest ending the evening early, acted as if nothing had happened, continued eating, and naturally changed the subject.

 "Your photography exhibition is also on Veteran's Day at the National Memorial, right? How are the preparations going?"  "I suppose well."

The answer sounded so distant he seemed to be talking about someone else. Giselle blinked, puzzled, but he offered her a calm smile, as if nothing was wrong.

 "My work finished as soon as I took and selected the photos. I only amused myself; the rest of the effort is done by others."  "I'm looking forward to seeing it. I'll go to the opening without fail."  "Then you can tell me how people react."  "You're not going to go?"  "Don't you think it would be better for everyone including me?"

He laughed lightly as he returned the question, but Giselle's heart sank. And not just because of her uncle's situation. Also because she was beginning to understand that, no matter how much she tried to avoid it, the conversation about him, that demon, was unavoidable. And he wasn't the only subject they couldn't escape.

 "I'll take care of finding a good home for the dog. Don't worry."  "Why? He seemed very calm. I can take care of him."

Edwin could no longer play along with Giselle. It didn't matter if she was feigning for him or for the other man: in his eyes, that stubbornness was nothing but a form of self-harm. He found it difficult to hide the mixture of emotions that overwhelmed him upon seeing her face maintaining that carefree expression with so much effort.

 "Giselle"  "I can change his name."  "You don't need to raise him. It's not your responsibility."

Words he had always wanted to say: that what happened to her dogs wasn't her fault either. He knew her well enough to know she would have understood the hidden message, but Giselle, even so, kept insisting.

 "I really can do it. I'll take charge."  "Stubborn as ever. Alright I suppose a dog is better than a baby."

He murmured it softly, almost so only she could hear it. And for the first time, the constant smile she wore like a perfect mask subtly cracked on her face. It was the sign that they were approaching another one of those subjects they couldn't avoid.
Chapter 131.
 "Loise, Dawson, wait outside for a moment. Leave the door ajar, and if you hear any commotion, come in immediately and take Giselle out."

The two men only obeyed after Giselle confirmed that the person giving the order was indeed the Duke. They left the dining room and stood guard in front of the half-open door.

