I also thought it was a conversation we had to have at some point.

For Edwin, it was undoubtedly an uncomfortable topic.

But now what made him more uncomfortable than the content of the conversation was Giselle's excessively courteous tone.

Why are you suddenly acting like this with me, so distant?

He felt there was a wall.

She had raised a barrier in her heart, and now she was protecting herself from him.
Chapter 132.
 "You're hurt."

Edwin took a step back.

 "Giselle, my opinion isn't the only valid one. It will only be the right answer for both of us if it's the right answer for you, too. Tell me sincerely: what do you wish for?"

Then would you love me?

For Giselle, that was the only possible answer.

What she truly longed for wasn't marriage. It was the source of all her humiliation and pain, but also her only balm: Edwin Eccleston's love.

Love me as a woman.

Every time he told her, "Ask me anything, and I will do it," Giselle repressed the impulse to blurt out that shameless request. Not out of decorum, but because she knew the truth:

You can't give what you don't have.

Love doesn't sprout from effort. Hadn't she been the one who, one day without warning, started seeing Edwin as a man and fell in love? Edwin needed that same instant of revelation, but miracles can't be manufactured at will.

Giselle didn't want to beg for the impossible or degrade herself further.

 "If you think marriage is the solution, then I"  "Wait"  "You speak first."  "I understand you feel responsible for what I went through, but thinking you must pay for it with a marriage"

I hate it.

If he had proposed marriage out of love, as man and woman, she would have been happy. Even if he had told her, "I love you, but my perverse nature prevents me from committing," the pain would have been more bearable.

But she hated that marriage was only an act of obligation. That her love for him was reduced to a debt to be paid felt cruel.

 "Did I offend you?"  "No."

But she couldn't tell him: "Now your sin is making me feel this," to a man who was only seeking to atone for his guilt.

 "Don't you think that's a bit outdated?"

The answer, unexpected, left Edwin speechless.

 "We no longer live in a time where spending the night together forces you to marry."

Am I that behind the times? And besides, it hadn't been "just one night." Edwin bitterly swallowed the thought that sprung up: What if we hurt the child?

 "Then, what should I do?"

Giselle bit her lip, pensive, before answering, but it wasn't what Edwin expected.

 "I know you will only feel peace if you assume your 'responsibility' in some way."

Giselle, there is no peace possible for me.

She was misinterpreting his need for atonement as a simple desire for relief.

 "Giselle, it's for your own good. I just want your heart to be at peace."  "But I am fine. I'm not so wounded that I need to be 'healed'."  "If you keep lying like that, there's no point in us struggling so much to talk."  "It's not a lie."  "Giselle."  "Don't you think I'm much better now than when I discovered you had another personality? Or am I the only one who notices?"

It was true: lately, Giselle didn't seem as fragile as before, and that disconcerted Edwin.

 "It was hard at first, I admit. Discovering I liked you in the worst possible way it was agonizing."

Even now, confessing it, she felt the same shame as then, as if she were naked before him, more exposed than if she truly were. When Edwin, with an expression more pained than hers, reached out his hand, Giselle shook her head.

 "I don't care now. After seeing you at your worstand your bestmoments, I guess the crush wore off."

Giselle's uncomfortable laugh was met with a bitter smile from him.

