Except love you. Right?

The next day, Sir Loise visited Giselle on the Magnolia Terrace. His reason was completely unexpected.

 "Her Majesty the Queen has decided to grant the Duke a decoration and knight him on the occasion of Veterans' Day."  "Really? It's not surprising for someone like him, but that's wonderful news. I would love to be there to see it."

However, Giselle, who was neither a royal nor an Eccleston, would not have the privilege of witnessing that glorious moment.

 "Neither you, nor anyone, will be able to see it."  "Why?"  "The Duke has decided to send his aide in his stead."  "What?"

There was no need to ask the reason: it was because of his malevolent personality.

 "But after the armistice, when he returned, wasn't he received by Her Majesty?"  "Back then, the Duke had not yet experienced how much of an uncontrollable lunatic that demon was."  "Ah"  "And there's no guarantee that the luck of that time will be repeated."  "You're right. Still, it's a shame."  "I agree."

Sir Loise let out a sigh before continuing.

 "But the problem is that this isn't just a simple 'what a shame'. However justified his reasons, isn't it a grave disrespect to Her Majesty? And he can't tell her the truth either."

Loise had expressed his concerns to the Duke, but the answer had been firm:

 "It would be far more insulting if I became a lunatic in front of Her Majesty. Tell her I have a contagious disease. Then they themselves will cancel the audience."

But of course, they couldn't use the excuse of a "contagious disease" every time the Duke had to appear in public.

 "The Duke cannot keep shutting himself away like this."  "It's true."  "That's why I thought if we could at least distinguish between him and that other one, perhaps the Duke could regain some of his daily life with more peace of mind. Yesterday, seeing you, the idea occurred to me. So"

Sir Loise adjusted his glasses with one hand and stared intently at Giselle. It was a habitual gesture of his when he had something important to say.

 "Could you teach me how to distinguish between the Duke and that other one?"  "How?"

Upon hearing the request, Giselle remembered something from her childhood. Her dog had had two male puppies, and one had been given to a neighbor. Although the other villagers always confused them, even blaming the wrong dog for killing their chickens, Giselle's family and their neighbors were never wrong.

Today, when asked how she differentiated the Duke from the demon, Giselle could only give the same answer as when asked how she distinguished those two dogs.

 "It's just I simply know."
Chapter 133.
 "Doesn't he look different?"

Loise, with an expression as perplexed as Giselle's, repeated the question.

 "What do you mean by 'different'?"  "The feeling he gives off."

Loise blinked behind his round glasses, as if he hadn't caught the slightest clue.

 "For starters, even his gaze is distinct."

Wasn't it obvious to those who knew him well? That's why, yesterday, Giselle hadn't understood that Loise didn't notice. But now it was he who didn't understand her. Not even Rita, who had worked under Edwin's orders during the war.

