His refusal was not born out of displeasure at being commanded, but out of fear: he was afraid that the others would also learn to differentiate them. That Giselle recognized him pleased him, but if the others managed it, it would be a problem.

 "Then there's nothing to be done. I have no reason to stay. I'll leave."

Unlike Edwin, his unstable gaze clung to Giselle, as if wanting to hold her back. But, at the same time, he stubbornly clung to Edwin's body, and only when Giselle took a step back did he decide to surrender.

