Rita was no different:

 "Ah, Lorenz! Didn't we agree to have dinner together?"  "Today?"  "No."

Giselle used a trick to call the other personality again and asked them once more if they noticed the difference, but both shook their heads again.

Since everyone was only staring intently at the eyes, the other man realized he was being distinguished by his gaze. He stood in front of the mirror and began to intensely study his own eyes. It wouldn't be obvious to others, but at that moment the perpetrator was rapidly alternating between taking and releasing the body, trying to imitate Edwin's gaze. But since Giselle always managed to recognize him without fail, there was no progress.

Lord. Demon. Lord. Lunatic. Lord. Idiot.

After observing the constant back and forth between Edwin and the other personality, dizziness began to overwhelm them. It was Loise, even before Giselle, who put his hand to his forehead and heavily collapsed into a chair. He took off his glasses, tightly closed his reddened eyes, and muttered in frustration:

 "This is the only method we have"

He seemed desperate upon realizing that his abilities were insufficient.

 "Although I have served the Duke the longest, I cannot recognize him What a shame"

While listening to Loise's complaints, Giselle suddenly remembered the words that the demon, furious in front of the mirror, had said to belittle her, treating her as a useless leech:

 "Even if you gave everything for him, to the Duke, you are not worth as much as an experienced subordinate."

Was it really like that?

 "What could you do, insignificant as you are?"

But there was something. Something only she could do.

 "It's not that there isn't another way."

Loise opened his eyes wide; the other two also turned their attention toward her. Under their expectant gazes, Giselle continued:

 "I could follow him everywhere."  "That's a good idea."  "Not you. Edwin."

Edwin's answer was obvious

 "No. Absolutely not."  "But"  "Giselle, I regret having to say this to you, but are you in your right mind?"

In Edwin's eyes, not only Giselle, but also the other two, seemed to have lost their minds.

How could the very people who were supposed to protect the girl from the demon inhabiting him now suggest she voluntarily approach that creature? It was utter madness.

