Loise and Dawson, ignorant of what Giselle had suffered during her confinement, believed her words. But Edwin, who knew every second of her torment, was not fooled.

 "Miss Bishop doesn't fear him, and he, curiously, seems to listen to her. We saw him go and come like an obedient dog today."  "Dawson is right."

Loise added, crossing a dangerous line.

 "Although he ignores the Duke's orders and mine, he easily succumbs to Miss Bishop's pleas. Frankly, it's admirable."

Dawson, taking it further, tried to convince him with the words that most repelled Edwin, achieving the exact opposite effect:

 "Yesterday, she even had the courage to kick out that thief as if nothing. Miss Bishop would have even made an excellent soldier."  "Your Grace, it's been six months of rejecting invitations and communiqués. You cannot keep hiding. It is for the good of the Ducal House and your own."

Unlike Dawson, Loise was astute enough to know how to appeal to Edwin's sense of duty. But if the safety of Giselle was on one side of the scale, nothing on the other sideno matter how much it accumulatedcould tip it.
Chapter 134.
 "Dawson and I, we promise not to take our eyes off you for a second. We won't leave you alone under any circumstances. It won't be different from now."  "That's true. And nothing happened yesterday either. Lord, you know I can't avoid him forever, right?"  "Giselle, you"

Don't you feel uncomfortable? After what that man did to you with this very face? To get over it, to sort out your feelings as you decided, it would be better not to see each other.

What the hell do you want from me?

The words Edwin swallowed in silence so as not to hurt Giselle kept piling up until he finally fell silent.

What on earth was she thinking? Perhaps, in her youth, she wasn't thinking at all. Her words sounded absurdly naive.

 "And don't you think Lorenz has also lowered his guard?"  That bastard, at this very moment, is only scheming how to stab you in the back after hearing that.

'It's not true.' 'Shut up, lunatic.' 'He's worse than I am. Didn't you see what he picked up on the battlefield? Even I'm afraid of him now.' 'Afraid? You gave away a dog!' 'You'll see. I'm right. While the "Duke" builds walls for his "dignity," I tear them down, even if they call me a scoundrel. Which of the two truly loves her?'

Murmurs. His head was chaos. After more than a year silent or speaking in incomprehensible tongues, now that man wouldn't stop giving his opinion about Giselle. He couldn't cover his non-existent mouth, and enduring his nonsense was an ordeal.

 "I'm not scared anymore."

And to top it all off, the absurd words echoing outside his head worsened the torment.

 "I am stronger than you think. You know that, right?"

At that moment, Edwin could not remain silent.

 "Everyone out. Except Giselle."

When the two guards went out and stood guard in front of the door, Edwin finally spoke the words he had suppressed.

 "Are you so strong that you tried to kill yourself over a comment from that man?"

At that instant, Giselle's expression was as if she had been slapped. Edwin couldn't help but feel the pain of his own sword stabbing her.

If he avoided touching Giselle's wounds, it wasn't out of dignity, but to care for her. But raising someone sometimes meant being the villain.

 "That"

Giselle moved her lips as if to reply, but finally pressed them together without saying anything. With her typical pride, she tried to hold his gaze, but her eyelids reddened, as if tears would burst forth at one more cold word from Edwin.

Where is your strength now?

Giselle seemed fragile, too fragile. Edwin approached her, wrapped her restless hands in his, and looked intently at her.

