In his mind, the other's voice insisted: 'I never wanted to kill her!' but Edwin ignored it. Meanwhile, Giselle dodged his words with another question:

 "He didn't even hit me"  "Does simply not touching you already make you feel safe?"

Does she seriously not fear a rapist just because he didn't hit her? Far from reassuring him, the girl's lack of fear caused him a worry that clouded his vision.

 "If that man, while receiving a decoration in the palace, calls you to his bed instead of staying still what would you tell him?"

Giselle's cheeks instantly burned, as if she had never expected Edwin to touch upon such a delicate subject.

 "Well, of course I'd tell him no!"  "And if he insists?"  "I will convince him with words. I know how to talk to him."  "Why you?"  "Because he listens to me."

Edwin didn't believe for a second that that selfish animal could have been 'domesticated,' but he let the comment slide.

