Edwin then understood that taking the dog hadn't been just about pride. She had succumbed to her own desire: to raise him until the end, to prove to that bastard that she no longer cared.

 "Giselle, sometimes losing is winning."

He had to teach that overly competitive girl that there are times when it's wiser to yield than to insist on winning. Today was the perfect opportunity.

So, after opposing it until the end, Edwin was about to send Giselle back when

 "Your Grace, I have a request to make of you."

Suddenly, Loise knelt before him. In more than twenty years of service, he had never done so.

 "I don't know what it is, but stand up and speak."

Loise had no reason to kneel. But his principal secretary, with unusual determination, ignored the order.

 "If I die serving you, I beg you to take care of my wife and daughters."

It wasn't a plea, but a declaration: he was willing to die for him, even in the face of that demon.

 "Your Grace, I am human, and I am afraid. And if you permit the insolence I am exhausted."

Loise had been the closest to Edwin since his return, the one who had endured the other man the longest. And in recent months, from Professor Fletcher's death to Edwin's suicide attempt and Giselle's kidnapping, he had shouldered every blow.

The stress had consumed him. When Edwin returned with Giselle to the mansion, Loise seemed to have aged years in days. Alone, he had to take on impossible tasks, like looking for a needle in a haystack after the other man's whims.

 "I know it is unworthy to ask this, especially after what happened to Miss Bishop due to my incompetence."  "Loise, that's not true."

If anyone should feel shame, it was Edwin, for demanding the impossible of him. Anyone else would have already resigned. But he couldn't tell him to leave: Loise wasn't asking for permission to retire, but for strength to continue.

 "I beg you to give me a chance. Just one."

"I am willing to die for you. Yield, even if it's just this once." That's what Loise was saying.

 "I will protect Miss Bishop as if she were my daughter. And I swear I will learn to distinguish you from him."

While Loise remained kneeling and Edwin, unable to coldly reject him, remained silent, Giselle intervened:

 "I also can't follow you everywhere because of school. I'll only be close when it's important. And Loise will need my help to learn to recognize him."

Sometimes losing is winning.

Perhaps that advice was more for Edwin than for her.

 "Duke Edwin Eccleston, of the Army Special Forces"

The royal secretary announced the first decorated hero while the hero, in full dress uniform, watched the guests from the platform.
Chapter 135.
Since the Swanho incident until the Third Constanza War, he had defended the kingdom against all threats, loyally serving Her Majesty the Queen and the homeland

He made no boast, maintaining a solemn silence, but the countless decorations embroidered on his uniform and his imposing physique exuded a majesty that overwhelmed those who looked at him, forcing them to listen to the feats he would never verbalize.

Edwin Eccleston was the man who shone brightest in the royal palaceeven in front of the monarch who held ultimate authorityeclipsing all other ostentation with his presence.

'That man is mine and no one else's.'

