 "Your Excellency may use this room."

The royal secretary, guiding the laureates to the waiting room where they could change, gave a separate room only to Edwin and his entourage. It seemed to be a mark of respect toward the ducal family.

As soon as they entered the private room, the ducal staff found their own tasks without any instruction and helped with the preparations. They deftly took the new medals and the symbols accompanying the knighthood from the chest, pinning them onto Edwin's uniform, who stood in front of the full-length mirror in the center of the room, without a moment's hesitation. It was obvious how countless times they had done this.

There was a brief exchange of words about the order in which the two crosses should be placed, but after Mr. Royce consulted a thick regulation book, there was no further conversation. Their professionalism was astonishing.

And Edwin was incredibly handsome, to the point of inspiring reverence. The blue ribbon of the order of knighthood, crossing his torso from his broad shoulder to the opposite waist, radiated refined elegance and dignity, while further enhancing his fat-free, triangular torso, adding a touch of wild masculinity.

On the left side of the uniform, where there wasn't enough space, the densely overlapping medals shone in gold and silver; on the right side hung a thick braided gold cord. If the decoration is too flashy, the person can be eclipsed by it and appear vulgar. However, Edwin's quiet presence calmly and skillfully dominated that ostentation.

Giselle felt immensely grateful for Edwin's carefree yet self-assured appearance, as if he had returned to the man he was before getting lost in his fight against the demon in his head.

As he finished dressing and put the bicorn on his head, their eyes met in the mirror. In that instant, his eyes, containing a warm blue light, curved gently. Thump-thump. Giselle's heart betrayed its owner's determination.

Living together, one rarely gets the opportunity to see someone fully dressed in formal wear with all their adornments. The attendants would have seen it from time to time, but for Giselle, it was the first time. The man now was the most similar to Edwin and, at the same time, the most unfamiliar.

It was such an enchanting sight that even a stranger would feel excited. So it was not Giselle's fault that her heart was beating without shame.

When the preparations finished and the attendants withdrew, he took the hilt of the ceremonial sword he wore at his waist with his white-gloved hand. The movement of unsheathing the long sword to verify it was fluid and natural.

 "What do you think about coming to the royal palace?"

Even just before the moment of appearing before thousands, tens of thousands of people, his calm demeanor when addressing Giselle without showing any sign of nervousness was admirable.

 "It's fascinating. It's similar and different from the ducal mansion."

She had seen the exterior of the royal palace, but it was her first time inside. As she had come to work as an assistant, she tried not to look like a child who had insisted on following Edwin. However, in front of Edwin, she couldn't help but revert to being an excited girl.

 "Thank you for bringing me."

Tac

Edwin sheathed the sword and narrowed his eyes slightly.

 "I should be the one thanking you. You haven't come for a visit. I feel sorry for you, who have come all this way and can only see familiar faces without being able to see the royal palace or the royal family."  "No, I came to see you."

She wanted to imprint in her eyes the moment her hero shone brilliantly. Of course, the Queen, whom she had only seen in blurry black and white photographs in the newspapers, was fascinating in person.

 "Your Excellency, it's time."

The secretary knocked on the door from outside. Therefore, they left the building, crossed the garden, and headed towards the palace's East Square. Along the way, the honor guard and the royal guard formed in several rows caught her attention. It wasn't the first time she had seen a military parade, but she had only watched it from the street, and it was the first time she had seen the preparation process, so this too was fascinating.

 "Tsk"

Rita, walking next to Giselle, scanned the soldiers in impeccable uniforms, rigid as statues, then clicked her tongue and muttered to herself.

 "Suddenly, I want to re-enlist."  "Do it."

Edwin, walking ahead, must have heard her, because he glanced at Rita over his shoulder.

 "Your position will still be open. Hawkins will love it. I'll have them call you tomorrow."  "Ah, no, Major!"

It was the first time she had seen Rita, always so carefree, so nervous.

 "Does an old man who always says his time has come really want to die?"

Rita slowed her pace, increasing the distance from Edwin, then, muttering so only Giselle could hear her, she kicked the edge of the flower bed with the tip of her shoe. A piece of mud stuck to her sole fell onto the dirt path.

It had been raining non-stop in the Richmond region since yesterday. Most of the other outdoor events were canceled, but the military parade would proceed as planned, so she was worried about Edwin, who would have to ride a horse in the rain, but luck was on their side and the rain ceased for a moment.

The march is normally done on foot, but today's laureates, the heroes, would be on horseback. The group stopped upon reaching a place where soldiers held several horses.

Edwin was given a white horse as elegantly adorned as the soldiers. After receiving the reins, he first took time to break the ice with the horse. When the curious horse brought its muzzle closer, Edwin stroked the bridge of its nose.

 "Good boy."

While Giselle watched the way Edwin treated the horse, as if spellbound, she instinctively shivered in that instant and unconsciously searched for his eyes.

It's Edwin, right?

She felt relieved, but the tension did not easily disappear. Seeing the hand that skillfully and affectionately stroked the horse's smooth neck and mane dried her throat. In the end, a chill even ran down her spine, and Giselle had no choice but to lower her head, forgetting her duty.

 "Giselle, are you feeling unwell?"  "Huh? No."

Giselle instantly erased her tearful expression and abruptly lifted her face. She smiled shyly like a child caught causing mischief out of boredom; the corner of Edwin's lips followed hers upwards before returning to a straight line the moment a whistle sounded in the distance.

Edwin nimbly climbed onto the horse without needing a stirrup or help from the attendants. His claim that he learned to ride a horse as soon as he learned to walk was no exaggeration. Although it was his first time riding in years, his movements were precise and unhurried. They say even animals recognize important people, and the white horse docilely carried him on its back without even a startle.

The man, with a riding crop in one hand and the reins in the other, looked at the gate beginning to open in the distance and then turned his gaze back to Giselle. Even under the shadow of the bicorn's brim, his warm eyes enveloped her. She looked into his eyes one last time and nodded.

 "May you fare well, Major."

Carried away by the atmosphere, she called him by his military rank instead of "Lord." In that instant, the officer on horseback stopped smiling and offered Giselle a solemn salute.

He immediately turned the horse's head and began to move away from Giselle. Thump-thump-thump-thump. Giselle harbored the vain hope that what was resonating in her chest now was the vibration of the horse's hooves hitting the ground.

Edwin's figure grew small before disappearing through the East Gate. Cheers were already audible from outside the castle walls.

 "Shall we go too, Miss Bishop?"
Chapter 137.
 Giselle left the royal palace with Rita through an entrance next to the East Gate. They walked almost running through the crowd that filled the sidewalk, in the opposite direction to Edwin.

The square in front of the balcony where the royalty would appear for the parade would be more than crowded. Giselle, who only cared about seeing Edwin, headed to the last section of the route, where there would still be some space to stand.

However, even the street where the parade would pass later was lined with citizens on both sides, and of course it was impossible to occupy the front row.

 "How about over there?"

While Giselle looked around without finding a gap where she could see Edwin, Rita pointed to a ledge on the outer wall of a building along the street. There, higher than Giselle, naughty children were already sitting in a row like little birds on a branch, and only a secluded space remained where barely two adults could fit.

If she climbed up there in a skirt, Edwin would scold her for behaving like an elderly lady.

But it's better than not seeing him.

 "It's fine."

With Rita's help, she clambered up the wall and sat on the outer ledge. Rita, who climbed up afterward, took something out of her bag and smiled shrewdly. They were binoculars. Giselle, admiring her exhaustive preparation, brought the binoculars to her eyes just as the child next to her asked his friend:

 "When are the fighter jets coming?"  "They're not coming today. Didn't you know?"

It had only drizzled and stopped here, but it was still raining heavily at the air base on the outskirts. That's why the air squadron's celebration flight was canceled this morning.

 "Tch I came to see that."

Besides that child, many citizens would have eagerly awaited the moment when the fighter jets majestically flew overhead. Among the disappointed people, Giselle was the only one who felt relieved. If it hadn't been canceled, Giselle wouldn't have been able to watch this parade and would have had to hide in some secluded palace restroom.

When a fighter jet passes overhead, she still screams and shrinks unconsciously. This is something she hasn't been able to correct no matter how hard she tries.

When she was going to Fullerton, once the sound of a fighter jet pierced the window during class. That day contributed to the stares and pointing Giselle received there.

Please, let it rain tomorrow too.

Tomorrow, at the Veterans' Day event to be held at the National Memorial, a celebration flight is also originally scheduled. She planned to sneak away in time, but if it is canceled due to rain like today, she can help with the event calmly.

 "They're coming!"

As soon as the children's shouts ceased, the military band's music began to be heard. The murmuring crowd quieted, and everyone turned their heads towards the end of the street at the same time.

In a short time, the head of the procession was close enough to be seen with the naked eye. Cheers were heard from the other side of the street, and camera flashes shone like sparks among the people. The flashes fired sequentially along the street, following a point in the center of the row. It was like a wave.

The wave of light approaches Giselle. It means Edwin is approaching. Soon, the image of a young officer on horseback was imprinted in Giselle's eyes through the binoculars. Although it was the same figure she had seen a moment ago, it felt different.

He looks like a victorious general.

The soldier, who rode the horse with an upright and firm posture, without wavering, was dazzling as a bronze statue.

Click, click, click

Even among the crowd gathered at Giselle's feet, camera clicks began to be heard, and flashes lit up. When Edwin arrived in front of the building, Giselle returned the binoculars to Rita and took the camera she had prepared. She wanted to capture this momentous moment not only in her memory but also in a photograph.

However, the instant he appeared in the viewfinder, Giselle could not press the shutter.

The image of the man reflected in the glass was a work of art. And that made her feel lonely. She felt like an anonymous spectator observing a unique masterpiece hung in a museum behind a "Do Not Touch" sign.

Is it because Edwin isn't looking at me?

When she looked at him through the camera lens, he was always facing Giselle. But today's Lord isn't looking at her. A new understanding gripped her finger above the shutter.

She felt foolish for worrying that he might see her behaving unladylike. The hero on the road walks looking only forward. It made no sense for him to look at the anonymous crowd standing at the edge of the path.

Giselle and Edwin belonged to different worlds, separated by an invisible wall like the viewfinder's glass. One layer because of the enormous difference in status, and another layer because of the difference in the temperature of their feelings.

The glass, no matter how many layers it has, can be broken. Today's Giselle had a bold thought that the past version, before being dragged away by the demon, would never have dared to imagine.

Edwin, even now, would gladly accept if Giselle insisted that he marry her. She could tear down the multiple layers of walls between them even resorting to an obstinacy that would shatter her last bit of pride.

The reason she doesn't is because she hopes that man will break the wall himself and extend his hand to the other side. By himself. Only because he desires it.

But he had already made it clear. That such a thing would not happen.

Edwin Eccleston swore to love only Giselle Bishop until the day he died, but he sentenced that he would never love her as a woman. Giselle would be loved forever, but she would not be loved romantically. She did not want to photograph this moment where she once again felt that satiating lack deeply.

 "In a photograph, not only the subject is photographed, but also the heart of the one who shoots."

It was a misfortune for both to paint Edwin's brilliant moment with her somber loneliness.

In the end, she had no choice but to take her finger off the shutter.

In the afternoon, a brief reception was held at the royal palace. In the various corners of the long banquet hall, groups of three or five people, a glass of champagne in hand, blossomed into conversations and laughter.

 "Since you've come this far, you should be promoted to Colonel."  "No, we should make him ascend to Colonel before he leaves, man."

Meanwhile, Edwin was approached by his superiors with stars on their shoulders.

 "Actually, with this amount of merit, it wouldn't be unreasonable for him to receive the rank of Colonel this time"  "He's too young."  "Besides, although he was promoted to Major by his own ability, it was an early promotion due to a special promotion in wartime, so there were many whispers behind his back."  "Of course, if someone knew the merits the Major accumulated in the last war, no one could object to his promotion to Colonel"

The General vaguely mentioned merits that could not be revealed and glanced sideways at Giselle, who was standing next to Edwin.

 "Lord, did that man say you are truly an executioner?"

When Giselle asked this recently, Edwin had no choice but to lie, saying no, although he regretted it.

 "I'm sorry, Major."

Even they, who probably regretted not being able to promote him, had no other option and specifically approached to apologize. They were worried that Edwin would feel dissatisfied with this and resign from the army, so they came to calm him down. The army could not help but misinterpret the reason why he had been on leave since his return.

 "Hold on a little longer. Once you overcome the Colonel hurdle, the ascent to Colonel will be a piece of cake."  "Duke Eccleston wouldn't have any reason to cling to the rank of Colonel, would he?"

As soon as they realized that the owner of the voice that had suddenly intruded was Crown Princess Helena, the Generals tensed up and showed respect. Giselle, who was standing next to Edwin, was also surprised and quickly bent her knees to greet the Crown Princess.

The curtsey with bent knees is a basic skill for ladies of high society. Edwin, who since his childhood had seen countless times women being criticized for this posture, assigned Giselle a teacher whom no one could ignore to teach her how to salute. Thanks to that, despite the suddenness, she did not miss the opportune moment and, although she bowed deeply, her posture did not waver at all.

As he usually did when he felt he had raised her well as an excellent socialite, Edwin looked at Giselle with a satisfied smile. But, for some reason, Giselle's face, which had risen after saluting, was completely red. As if she had committed some mistake.

Only after turning his gaze toward the Crown Princess did Edwin realize the reason. The Crown Princess had an expression that she had never before seen such a vulgar and classless salute. He felt disgusted, but not surprised.

Had the Crown Princess ever stopped disparaging talented people? Edwin, who had already experienced that woman's arrogance, knew it wasn't Giselle's fault, but this girl didn't know it.

 "You were perfect."

He whispered in Giselle's ear so that others couldn't hear him.

 "It is the Crown Princess who lacks manners."

Giselle's eyes, which had been directed at the Crown Princess, opened wide and turned to Edwin.

Even if no one else could hear it, was it alright to say such things in front of the Crown Princess?

Anyone else would have clucked their tongue saying he didn't know the fear of royalty, but in the case of Edwin, there was no doubt that he was the intrepid Eccleston, which made people marvel.
Chapter 138.
 "Ah, would Duke Eccleston care about an insignificant military decoration?"

The generals, who had been about to impose a hut upon someone who owned a mansion, lowered their heads to the Crown Princess and changed their strategy.

 "But, wouldn't Her Highness feel safer if a competent commander remained in the army?"

The Crown Princess tilted her head to the side, with a sulky expression.

 "The Duke does not have to swear loyalty to our monarch of Mercia only from the army."  "Ah, of course."  "That's right."

The Crown Princess's main point was that he should swear allegiance elsewhere. Edwin understood it, but pretended not to.

 "By the way, Duke, how many years have passed? I came to greet you after so long."

The formal apology that a subject should offer to his Lord, for not having gone first to greet Her Highness, did not come from Edwin's lips. Because the Crown Princess was not seeking him now as her sovereign.

 "I am glad you returned safe and sound."  "Thank you."  "It was meant to be. It seems my prayers finally reached the ears of the gods."

At this point, Edwin concluded that he should leave that place.

Of course, he should be grateful. But it wasn't just about being fed up with those arrogant words.

The fact that the Crown Princess, haughty and insensitive, had said that she had even prayed for him, caused the alarm that had been ringing in his head for a while to intensify even further.

The Crown Princess saw him as a man.

From the moment she had taken the trouble to personally hand him the medal, an insignificant task that only corresponded to him, the situation had been suspicious, and his dire premonition had finally come true.

It was obvious that her disdain for Giselle's etiquette also aimed to control the annoyance standing next to him. The Crown Princess was not the first woman who had messed with the innocent Giselle without even realizing that this was a negative factor for Edwin. In the end, the Crown Princess was also a woman with a petty heart, with nothing worthy of respect, like the others.

And he didn't even think of her as a woman.

 "It has been a pleasure, Your Highness. Then, I will withdraw, I have other matters to attend to."

Edwin took Giselle and moved away from the group. Several curious and expectant glances turned to where he would go, but Edwin's eyes moved without hesitation toward the corner of the hall he had been observing until then.

About six guests surrounded a man, listening intently to his story. The man, dressed in a uniform decorated with the insignia of Sergeant, showed pride on his face, as if he were telling the story of how he had come to be there today. Edwin made a gesture with his eyes toward the sergeant and asked Giselle:

 "Do you know that man?"

Sergeant Thomas Ritzka was from Rozelle. And the reality for those from Rozelle was that, due to the deeply rooted custom of viewing them with prejudice for being mixed-race with the enemy country, their merits were rarely recognized, even after achieving great feats.

Even so, the fact that the sergeant had received a decoration directly from the king was due to the extraordinary feats he had performed on the battlefield, to the point that even high society, which detested any contact with those from Rozelle, had approached of their own free will to listen to him.

For Giselle, who would have to fight all her life against contempt and discrimination for being from Rozelle, a hero of her same ethnicity could be a good example to follow, instilling confidence in her. And, to be honest, it was also for Edwin himself.

'Do you really think changing your name was an act of respect toward you? If the Duke loved you as you are, he would have loved even your humble origin.'

He was not in a position to reprimand Giselle for foolishly falling for the provocation of a snake-tongued demon. He was no different.

Edwin had not changed Giselle's name with the intention of denying her origin. But to others it might seem so. He didn't care what others thought, but he didn't want Giselle to misunderstand.

'Giselle, I was never ashamed that you were from Rozelle. Do you know that?'

He wanted to prove it with actions instead of words. Of course, no matter how good his intentions were, the right thing to do was to first ask Giselle her opinion and then act.

 "The surname sounds familiar."

The fact that she responded like that without him mentioning the name meant that Giselle had also been interested in that person and had been observing him.

 "Do you want to go say hello? You don't have to if you feel uncomfortable."

Giselle hesitated, as if undecided, but finally nodded. Edwin waited for a moment, deliberately delaying, and only approached with Giselle when the crowd around the sergeant dispersed.

 "Sergeant Thomas Ritzka."  "Major Eccleston?"

The moment he heard his name, the sergeant's gaze, which had always shone with intelligence, became lost and empty. As if it were a great surprise that Edwin spoke to him, the sergeant saluted an instant later.

 "Sergeant Thomas Ritzka, it is an incredible honor to meet you, Major!"  "Congratulations. I heard a lot about your exploits during the war."  "R-really?"  "Your bravery and ingenuity were remarkable. Thanks to you and your men risking your lives to cut the enemy communication lines during the Battle of Herenberg Hill, my men were saved. I wanted to thank you in person when I met you."

The sergeant took Edwin's extended hand with both hands, and his eyes began to moisten, in a way that did not seem characteristic of such a rock-solid soldier.

 "Receiving a decoration alongside the Major is the best day of my life. Anyway, I wanted to meet and thank the benefactor who prevented the massacre of those from Rozelle and had it recorded. I doubted whether to approach this celebration and cause a nuisance, but having you speak to me first makes me feel overwhelmed and ashamed. I am also deeply moved that the Major remembers my history in such detail."  "You would not be a nuisance. And that I remember you is entirely your merit. It must have been difficult for you not to be recognized like the others due to your origin."

The sergeant's eyes reddened. He nodded, pressing his lips tightly as if trying to suppress a lump that had formed in his throat.

 "I can only thank you for acknowledging it."  "It's nothing. Ah, by the way, I have someone to introduce you to."

Edwin turned toward Giselle, who had been silently observing behind him. Out of habit, he tried to wrap his arm around her waist to bring her closer, but stopped his hand just before touching her.

 "She is"

He decided that the right thing to do was to let Giselle choose what name to introduce herself with and whether to reveal that she was from Rozelle.

 "Do you want to introduce yourself?"

Giselle looked around with a somewhat tense expression and then nodded.

 "Nice to meet you. My name is Giselle Bishop."

He thought she wouldn't want to reveal that she was from the same region, but Giselle moved her lips for a moment and then continued her introduction in a low voice.

 "My original name is Rudnik. I am also from Rozelle."  "Rudnik?"

The sergeant narrowed his eyes as if the name were familiar.

 "Do you know me?"

To Giselle, only his surname sounded familiar. She didn't recall there being a young man named Thomas Ritzka in her town.

 "You don't know me, but I think I do know your father. Isn't he Mr. Rudnik, whose wife was a great beauty, all his children were blonde, and he only had one daughter?"  "Yes, that's right."

It turned out that Sergeant Ritzka was from another town and knew Giselle's father.

 "What happened to your family?"  "I am the only one who survived."

A pain fundamentally different from those who lamented an unknown tragedy was etched on the sergeant's face.

 "I had already been recruited by then, so I avoided the massacre, but my family was not so lucky. You must have suffered a lot there at a young age, without parents."  "I was fine. The Duke saved me."

Giselle had a habit of changing the subject when receiving pity for what had happened to her in her childhood.

 "Then is the orphan from Rozelle that the Major said he had taken in the daughter of Mr. Rudnik?"  "Yes, that's right. Thanks to the Duke I am alive, and today I could see the royal palace and even met the Queen up close."

Edwin's brow, which had remained on the sidelines listening to the conversation, furrowed slightly.

 "What a way to say you came for a stroll. That child has already grown into such a wonderful adult that she helps me with my work."  "Really? Wow, this is incredible! It is very encouraging for us from Rozelle. The more people from Rozelle contribute to the country and move toward mainstream society, the less prejudice and discrimination there will be. Never give up and believe that everything you do raises the status of all of Rozelle. Be firm and proud in everything you do."  "Yes."

Stories about her roots had always made Giselle feel disheartened or defensive. It was the first time she felt so moved. Giselle nodded firmly.

 "Like you, Sergeant."

A satisfied smile spread across the sergeant's face.

 "It would also be good for you to become a soldier like me and serve the country."  "No, enlistment is absolutely forbidden. For a student, studying hard is patriotism."

He had tried to encourage her, but ended up inciting Giselle to join the army. It was impossible for Edwin to overlook that absurd suggestion.
Chapter 139.
 "Ah, excuse me. I didn't know she was a student and committed an imprudence."  "She is not just any student, but the top of her class at Kingsbridge. She will go far someday."

The sergeant's eyes widened in surprise, and he let out an exclamation of admiration; his eyes even welled up.

 "The Rudnick family, who are in heaven, must be very happy. And surely they must be deeply grateful for your great kindness, my Commander."

No. Perhaps they would want to throw into hell the demon who did something terrible to their sole surviving daughter, their only child, and drove her to the brink of death.

Edwin was not ashamed of Giselle. He was ashamed of himself for feeling proud of her.

The look from Helena, who had her back to him and was watching the Duke interacting with a simple Rozelle soldier, could not have been kind.

 "The Duke's first public appearance after his return was the graduation of that Rozelle orphan?"

Her mother, who knew her intentions well, approached to annoy her.

 "Today he even brought her to an official event to present her to people. Seeing that he is trying to introduce her into high society, it seems he did not take in and raise that orphan child just out of charity."

Even during the graduation ceremony, the Duke did not look at the stage, but kept his gaze fixed on the young blonde woman sitting below. Since then, she had a bad feeling.

And when she casually ignored that child, the Duke turned away, completely disregarding the Crown Princess. The bad feeling grew even stronger.

'It seems they have a deeper relationship than I thought.'

Her mother, a shrewd woman like an old fox, knew exactly how to stimulate Helena's anxiety.

 "Was the rumor true that he was raising a child to turn her into his mistress? How indecent. He truly is the most alpha male of the Ecclestons."

How dare she defame the Duke, without any foundation, saying he had an illicit relationship with a Rozelle orphan to push her point of view?

 "According to rumors, I am also a low-performing student who forced her way into university using my power, something impossible with my grades. It is surprising that someone who knows well about this believes unfounded rumors. Even a smart monarch cannot deceive age."

For the Crown Princess, equally arrogant with everyone, her mother was no exception.

 "Don't you think I know the Duke better than you, Mother?"  "Well, that's a funny joke. What would a brat with rose-tinted glasses know about men? Besides, if someone who doesn't know us hears this, they might misunderstand that you have great intimacy with the Duke. Although it seems that you do believe it."

However, her arrogant and biting tongue was, in fact, an inheritance from her mother.

 "You've only seen him a couple of times at Alice's birthday parties, haven't you?"

Her cousin Alice, of the same age, was an Eccleston on her mother's side, so she was also the Duke's cousin. Thanks to that connection, she had met the Duke once a year since she was a child.

For a child, even a difference of one or two years feels large. Therefore, back then, she did not dare to speak to the Duke, who seemed like a distant adult. Although she had eyes of a child and thought he was a handsome, classy gentleman, she felt nothing more.

It was only when Helena was on the ambiguous border between childhood and adulthood that she saw him differently. After he rescued her like a knight from a difficult situation, without boasting of his mature composure, she fell in love with him.

At that time, Charles Eccleston was alive and Edwin Eccleston was the younger son of the dukedom. A spare son of a noble family was the perfect candidate for Prince Consort. Although he was unmarried, that did not seem to be an obstacle at all. Helena's father had also been unmarried, but he could not resist the pressure from her mother and her surroundings, and finally yielded in his decision. So Helena insisted with her mother

 "You are too young to talk about marriage."

Her mother forbade her to mention the subject again. Helena truly believed that her age was the problem and waited until she was the right age to marry. Meanwhile, Charles Eccleston died, and the man Helena had chosen as her husband became the Duke.

That Duke Eccleston himself would become Prince Consort was something that would make anyone gasp and shake their head. Having no choice, Helena gave up and, after graduating from university, met one after another the Prince Consort candidates her mother had chosen, but none pleased her.

Helena's heart was already occupied by another man.

She had always lived a life enjoying only the best. How could she settle for something second-rate? Helena had to have what she wanted. Unthinkable as it was that Duke Eccleston would become Prince Consort, it was not prohibited by law.

 "Helena, a man is not just his appearance. Didn't you learn anything from seeing me suffer because of your father?"  "Mother, you and I are different. The Duke is not just his appearance."  "Of course, there is also the Eccleston Dukedom. What would the Duke lack that would make him want to merge his family with ours and let his son inherit Crowley instead of Eccleston just to become Prince Consort?"  "That remains to be seen."

It was an announcement that she planned to do something in the future. For the Queen, the fact that her eldest daughter resembled her was generally a source of pride, but when their wills clashed, it was terribly problematic.

