Her mother gestured with her eyes, as if saying that the Duke's behavior at that moment directly contradicted her words. He was, precisely, extending his hand toward the waist of the Rozelle orphan next to him.

 "Isn't that a familiar and comfortable gesture?"  "Familiar?"

Helena ignored her mother's mockery.

 "He considers her a daughter, not a woman."

However, the Duke retracted from touching her, as if it were a shameful act that should not be shown to others, thus refuting Helena's belief.

Although raising an orphan as if she were a pet seemed peculiar, she didn't believe it would be an obstacle.

No. It won't be.

The reception marked the end of the event. As they left, Giselle got into the co-pilot's seat of the same car as Edwin, just as they had arrived. The escort car ahead left first, followed by Rita's car and then a line of attendants' vehicles.

Only after leaving the palace and entering the road did Giselle finally relax the tension that had kept her entire body rigid. Fortunately, the event ended without incident.

That Edwin had tried to delegate such an important event, where his presence was so significant, to his assistant Experiencing it firsthand turned out to be even more shocking. It was also a relief that such a waste did not occur.

 "Good job, Giselle."

Edwin, sitting diagonally behind, complimented Giselle. She felt uncomfortable being the only one praised when Sir Loise and Rita were also present.

 "Ah, I didn't do anything special"

At that moment, something appeared suddenly next to Giselle's face, interrupting her answer. Turning her head, she saw a blue velvet box the size of a palm.

 "Take it."

Inside was the commemorative victory coin that the Royal Mint had just issued. Officially it was a commemoration of the armistice, but the Mercia government, taking advantage of the fact that the enemy country had signed the agreement under conditions close to surrender, did not hesitate to use the expression "victory" and even created souvenirs.

Among them, the most valuable coin, minted in pure gold and of which only a few units were made, was given as a gift to today's honorees. Edwin was giving Giselle, with total naturalness, an object of great collection value.

 "This?"  "I don't have space in my wallet."

The man who always gave coins to Giselle because he found them bothersome, tried to give her even the commemorative coin with that excuse. The attendants were in charge of the objects the palace gave away and loaded them into the car, so she wondered why he had taken only that one separately. Giselle received it gratefully, but grumbled shyly.

 "How am I going to keep the prize a hero receives?"  "Because today's heroine is you."  "He is absolutely right."

Sir Loise, sitting next to Edwin, added:

 "If it hadn't been for Miss Bishop, we wouldn't have been able to carry out today's event smoothly. I also wanted to express my gratitude with a gift, but I cannot surpass what the Duke has given you."  "Loise, it's troublesome that you try to one-up me."

Edwin's light joke, as before, sparked a warm joy in Giselle's heart.

 "I am glad I could help the Duke return to normal."

For that, Edwin was also relieved, but at the same time uncomfortable. Was it necessary for Giselle to sacrifice even her night for his half-day?

As soon as he thought about the price of his half-day of freedom, Edwin sank beneath the surface of consciousness.

 "Pretty."

The warm atmosphere of the car abruptly cooled with that single word.

 "Now you have to go out with me."  "When did I say I would go out with you?
Chapter 140.
“To say something so outrageousthat you would date Lord’s other selfand do it right in front of everyone!”

While Giselle suddenly retorted, Rita pretended not to hear, continuing to grumble about the situation. Sir Loise, for his part, used his arm to block the space between the front and back seats, preventing that man from touching Giselle.

“It’s early for dinner. Come back later.” “We have to reserve a place in advance. Where do you want to go?” “I will eat at my house.”

Right after the military parade, many people would recognize Edwin. If they dined together in public, strange rumors might arise.

“Then I’ll decide what we do in the meantime. Dawson, to Magnolia Terrace.” “...My house? Why?”

What was he planning to do there? Was he going to say another crazy thing in front of everyone? Giselle tensed up.

“To walk our little dog.”

The answer did not match her worst expectation. Even so, Giselle did not relax. Rita glanced at her, noticing her stiff face. She didn't know which attitude was the correct one.

“Let’s go to Magnolia Terrace.”

Upon arriving in front of Giselle's house, the man entered without ceremony, as if it were his own home. A dog, especially affectionate towards people, ran out to greet him, jumping around and wagging its tail, as if remembering him after only one day. It seems this dog will never be a good guardian.

“Eddie, how are you?”

Giselle, who was intently watching the man and the dog from behind, quickly stepped in to correct him:

“It’s Loddy.” “Loddy?” “Lorenz. Loddy is his nickname.”

Giselle had given the dog a name derived from his. Realizing that ‘Lorenz’ was no longer exclusively his, the man’s smile completely vanished.

Shortly after, a sarcastic grimace appeared on his face, but it did not entirely hide the humiliation he felt. The pleasure born from the displeasure of that devil, though petty, was always sweet.

“Natalia, I see you absolutely love my gift. You even gave a simple dog a nickname?”

It also mortified him that she had baptized the animal with a nickname she never gave him. When the man reached his hand toward the dog’s neck, Giselle felt a sharp lurch in her chest. Will he do it out of jealousy? Or to hurt him?

“Loddy, come here.”

The dog, which already recognized its name and commands, broke free from the man and ran toward Giselle. Every time the animal approached, she felt a knot in her chest that made it difficult to breathe. Even so, she had called him countless times as a tactical sacrifice for her vengeance today. She never thought she would end up using him to prevent the devil from taking out his anger on the dog.

“Have you been a good boy at home?”

The dog, happy to see its owner, rubbed against her legs excitedly. Giselle, defiant, scratched its neck while smiling at the devil who was observing her closely.

Look at me. It doesn't affect me. It doesn't affect me. It doesn't affe...

The dog stopped moving and looked up at her, happily panting. Giselle did not fear the animal. She feared that innocent devotion.

Thump, thump, thump!

Her heart was thundering in her chest, right beneath her sternum, and her insides churned with nausea. She normally avoided the dog's gaze, but with him watching her, she had no choice.

“Loddy, let’s go for a walk.”

She had no choice but to distract the animal. She quickly put on its leash and exited through the back door. They were walking by the lake behind the house when Sir Loise interceded, placing himself between Giselle and the man. That man glared at him, as if considering him an obstruction.

“Get out of here, you worthless salary thief.” “You were the one who said we could assign you dozens of bodyguards and assistants.”

Giselle intervened instead of Sir Loise, who could not speak freely to that scoundrel occupying Edwin’s body.

“And show Sir Loise some respect.”

Pff. The man let out a mocking laugh.

“Why? This man is my servant.” “Your servant? He is Edwin’s secretary. And Edwin himself wouldn't treat an older man that way, unlike you, who never learned manners.” “And you did? Because now you’re disrespecting your elder.” “My elder?”

This time, it was Giselle’s turn to laugh sarcastically.

“Does a one-year-old brat dare to say anything to an adult?”

A one-year-old brat? Rita, who was walking behind Giselle, couldn’t hold back a laugh, even though she knew it was inappropriate.

“Listen, you brat. You are not Edwin. You are just a one-year-old orphan who fell from the sky with no parents and is living as a dependent in someone else’s house.”

Rita no longer even tried to disguise it. Instead, she held her breath. As the two looked at each other with murderous eyes, Sir Loise silently sweated between them.

“Natalia Rudnik, and what are you?” “When have I ever denied what I am? I’m just giving you a piece of advice from a more experienced leech. Learn your place, little leech, behave.” “Ah, so you do know your place”

How dare you harbor ambitions for Edwin Eccleston’s love? It was obvious he wanted to attack her with that, but the man stopped mid-sentence. His gaze had shifted toward the lake behind Giselle. Perhaps he was afraid that if he pressed her weak point again, she would jump into the water to kill herself.

“To lose is to win.”

He repeated the words Edwin used to say, then resumed his walk. Behind them, Rita let out the air she had been holding.

“June 13th.”

The man, who had been walking in silence until then, suddenly blurted out a meaningless date. When Giselle looked at him confused, he, as if he had been waiting for it, clarified:

“My birthday.”

Anger surged, and Giselle couldn't contain herself.

“Do you have no conscience or intelligence? You ruin my birthday and expect me to remember yours?” “I’m giving you the chance to ruin mine.”

Did he really expect her to believe he was doing it out of remorse? A parasite with no family, no friends, whose only ties were his enemies... perhaps, for him, any recognitionwhether celebration or cursewas better than oblivion.

“I don’t need it. I’ll forget it.”

Upon hearing that she wouldn't remember it, his blue eyesmore turbid than the lake in the rainconfirmed what Giselle already suspected: her conjecture was correct.

In the end, they ate dinner at Giselle's house. As in the Residence, Rita and Sir Loise flanked the couple while they shared a small table, under the watchful gaze of both.

“Natalia, what are you doing tomorrow night?”

Giselle left her glass suspended in the air, not because of the name he used, but because of the brazen act he was committing under the table.

The man slid the tip of his shoe between hers. It was his way of saying that what he really wanted to do with Giselle was not to dine, but to open her legs. She clenched her thighs tightly, warning him:

“What you’re doing now, Sir Loise and Rita can’t see... but Edwin can.”

Only then did the other two notice something was happening under the table and moved closer. Giselle shook her head to stop them.

“If you want to ensure I never see you again, keep going.”

The threat worked: the intrusive movement between her legs suddenly ceased. He looked at her with resentment, but finally withdrew his foot.

“They say love is a chain”

Why does he insist on pretending to be a fool madly in love, with tender and dramatic glances?

“Natalia, you are the kind of woman for whom a man who only lives in the present foregoes today’s pleasure just to see your face tomorrow.”

That “passionate declaration of love” was a calculated insult designed to embarrass her in front of the others. His revenge for having humiliated him earlier, forcing him to obey like a dog. But it didn't end there.

“If even someone like me loses his mind over you why doesn’t the Duke love you?”

He used his own unrequited love as a leash, while hanging hers on the gallows for public execution.

Calmly. With elegance.

If she reacted with overflowing emotions, it would only please him more. Giselle suppressed an internal scream, inhaled deeply, and exhaled before shouting:

“Loddy!”

The dog, who was sniffing in the hallway, ran in with his ears and tongue flying. When she threw him a leftover piece of bread, ‘Lorenz the dog’ wagged his tail enthusiastically. Meanwhile, ‘Lorenz who wasn't even a dog’ sharpened his gaze.

For him, it was a trivial revenge. For her, a miserable patch: forgetting one pain with another.

